      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Here's a simple implementation of the `get_dependencies` function using a recursive approach with Dutch spaces tokenization.\n\n```python\ndef get_dependencies(sentence):\n    tokens = sentence.split()\n    graph = {}\n\n    def build_graph(tokens):\n        R glob = {\"shows\": 1, \"of\": 1, \"signs\": 1, \"acute\": 1, \"respiratory\": 1, \"distress\": 1}\n        head = None\n        for j, t in enumerate(tokens):\n            if t in R glob:\n                if not head:\n                    head = t\n                else:\n                    if head not in graph:\n                        graph[head] = [t]\n                    else:\n                        graph[head].append(t)\n        return head, graph\n\n    head, graph = build_graph(tokens)\n    dependencies = []\n    for key, target_list in graph.items():\n        for target in target_list:\n            dependencies.append((key, target))\n    return dependencies\n```\nThis function works by identifying the head word in each relation, then building a graph with the target words. It iterates over the graph to collect all dependencies. You can adjust this function according to your specific needs.",
